{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529021"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:50:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:50:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14354"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14354"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.62,0.25,0.08,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7049"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78670"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7049"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14354"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64013"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1374"},{"type":"tags","id":"4419"},{"type":"tags","id":"4421"},{"type":"tags","id":"4422"},{"type":"tags","id":"12805"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16774"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17285"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17329"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26933"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78670"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the labour ward with her first pregnancy at 39 weeks of gestation. She reports regular, painful contractions for the past four hours. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a term-sized fetus in cephalic presentation. Vaginal examination shows the cervix is 4 cm dilated, 80% effaced, and the fetal head is at station -2. The midwife explains that they will be monitoring her labour progress closely.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following correctly describes the expected rate of cervical dilation for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Less than 0.5 cm per hour","0.5-1 cm per hour","1-1.5 cm per hour","1.5-2 cm per hour","Greater than 2 cm per hour"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question tests understanding of normal labour progress, particularly the expected rate of cervical dilation during the active phase of labour for a primigravida (woman in her first pregnancy).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003E0.5-1 cm per hour\u003C/strong\u003E. This represents the average rate of cervical dilation for a primigravida in active labour. It\u0027s important to note that this is an average expectation, and individual women may progress slightly slower or faster than this rate while still being within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELess than 0.5 cm per hour\u003C/strong\u003E would be considered too slow for normal labour progress. If labour were progressing this slowly, it might indicate labour dystocia or arrest of labour, which would warrant further assessment and potential intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1-1.5 cm per hour\u003C/strong\u003E is faster than the average rate for a primigravida, though it may still be within normal limits for some women. This rate is more typical of multiparous women (those who have had previous pregnancies).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1.5-2 cm per hour\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Egreater than 2 cm per hour\u003C/strong\u003E both represent more rapid progress than the average expectation for a primigravida. While not necessarily abnormal if the woman and fetus are coping well, these rates are significantly faster than typically seen in first-time mothers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s crucial to remember that labour progress should be monitored using a partograph, which allows for visual representation of cervical dilation over time. The partograph also includes other important parameters such as fetal heart rate, maternal vital signs, and descent of the fetal head. While the rate of cervical dilation is a key indicator of labour progress, it should always be considered in the context of other clinical findings and the overall wellbeing of both mother and fetus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding normal labour progress is essential for identifying deviations that may require intervention. However, it\u0027s also important to recognize that labour can vary significantly between individuals, and clinical decision-making should take into account the full clinical picture rather than relying solely on cervical dilation rates.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Normal cervical dilation in active labour is expected to progress at an average rate of 0.5-1 cm per hour for nulliparous women and 1-2 cm per hour for multiparous women.","The active phase of labour typically begins at 4-6 cm cervical dilation.","Partographs are essential tools for monitoring labour progress and identifying deviations from normal patterns."],"references":["Gill P, Henning JM, Carlson K, Van Hook JW. Abnormal Labor. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 [updated 2023 Jun 14]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459260/","Neal JL, Lowe NK, Ahijevych KL, Patrick TE, Cabbage LA, Corwin EJ. \u0022Active labor\u0022 duration and dilation rates among low-risk, nulliparous women with spontaneous labor onset: a systematic review. J Midwifery Womens Health. 2010 Jul-Aug;55(4):308-18. doi: 10.1016/j.jmwh.2009.08.004. PMID: 20630357; PMCID: PMC2904982.","World Health Organization.  WHO recommendations for augmentation of labour. World Health Organization. 2014. Available from: https://iris.who.int/bitstream/handle/10665/112825/9789241507363_eng.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64013"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14354"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64013","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64013"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T07:08:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T07:09:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7049"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78670"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0